"'''Queen of the South'''" is an [[instrumental]] [[song]] by [[Bill Drummond]] on his [[1986]] [[country music|country]] / [[folk music|folk]] album, [[The Man (album)|The Man]].

Bill Drummond is from [[New Galloway]] in southwest [[Scotland]] and is a self confessed fan of [[Dumfries]] football club [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]]. When interviewed for the club's website Drummond stated that his allegiance to the club stemmed from them being relatively local to where he came from.<ref>[http://www.qosfc.com/ClubNews/ViewFullStory/tabid/151/selectmoduleid/498/ArticleID/283/reftab/36/Default.aspx Bill Drummond interview for the official Queen of the South website]</ref> The name of the club comes from a local poet, David Dunbar who stood for parliament in the [[General Election]] of 1857. In one of his addresses he referred to Dumfries as ''Queen of the South'' and this become synonymous with the town. This was the popular choice for the name of the professional football club formed after the end of [[World War 1]] in Dumfries in 1919.<ref>[http://www.qosfc.com/AboutQueens/ClubHistory/tabid/164/Default.aspx Queen of the South F.C. Official history]</ref>

The song is the sixth track on ''The Man'' and is solely a Drummond composition. The album was released by [[Alan McGee]]'s [[Creation Records]].

